## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 6+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — the entire abort mechanism is removed
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** by the runtime

### Why It Was Removed

`Thread.Abort()` was fundamentally unsafe — it could interrupt code mid-execution (even inside `finally` blocks or `lock` statements), corrupt shared state, and cause orphaned locks. `ResetAbort()` was a band-aid that masked these issues.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false)
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait up to 2 seconds for graceful shutdown
            using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
            try
            {
                await _workerTask.WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                // Worker didn't finish in time — it's already been told to
                // cancel; log and move on. There is no forced kill equivalent.
                Log.Warning("Worker did not shut down within timeout.");
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Expected — the worker saw the token and exited
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Monitor.Wait` or synchronous I/O, `CancellationToken` won't interrupt it. You **must** convert to async APIs (`await reader.ReadAsync(token)`) or use token-aware blocking (`BlockingCollection.Take(token)`). |
| **No forced kill exists** | There is no `.NET 8` equivalent to `Abort()`. Design for cooperative cancellation — every long operation must check/accept the token. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` is dead code** | It compiles but never triggers. Replace with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. |
| **Token must flow everywhere** | If `ProcessItem` calls 5 methods deep, the token must propagate to the lowest-level I/O call, or cancellation won't be timely. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | `_running = false` can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` integrates with `async/await`, `WaitHandle`, and `BlockingCollection` natively. |

### If You Can't Go Fully Async

For synchronous-only code (e.g., CPU-bound loop, legacy library):

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        try
        {
            // Use token-aware blocking instead of bare Thread.Sleep / Monitor.Wait
            var item = _queue.Take(token); // throws OCE on cancel
            ProcessItem(item);
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // check between steps
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

### Also Consider `BackgroundService`

If this runs in ASP.NET Core or a Generic Host app, inherit from `BackgroundService` — it wires up cancellation, lifetime, and DI for you:

```csharp
public class MyProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration:
builder.Services.AddHostedService<MyProcessor>();
```
